    "question": "How does television production machinery convert reality into signals?",
    "answer": "Television production machinery performs the remarkable function of **bridging physical reality and electronic broadcasting** through signal conversion.\n\nThe process involves two primary conversions:\n\n**Visual Conversion (Camera):**\n- The television camera lens captures **light reflected from physical scenes** and objects.\n- Internal sensors convert these optical images into **electrical video signals** that represent the original scene in electronic form.\n- These signals can be transmitted live or stored on recording media.\n\n**Audio Conversion (Microphone):**\n- The microphone captures **sound waves** from the environment—including speech, music, and ambient noise.\n- It converts these acoustic waves into **electrical audio signals** that can be processed and transmitted.\n\nThis dual technical transformation allows **intangible real-world moments** to be captured, preserved, transmitted across distances, and viewed by millions of audience members far removed from the original event."
